(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 10 :title "Chapter 10 — A tiny compiler" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/10-a-tiny-compiler.md" :size 3716 :sha256 "ef281a12c7ff3168" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-10\ntitle: A tiny compiler\nbook: reference\nchapter: 10\nof: 16\npart: I\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane Q9)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\nprev: 09-environments\nnext: null\n---\n\n# Chapter 10 — A tiny compiler\n\nThe book closes on the small step from interpreter to compiler — turning Scheme forms into instructions for a tiny virtual machine.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A compiler is what happens when the interpreter looks at the code once and produces something faster to run later. The compiled thing carries the shape but runs on a simpler machine.\n\n## The instruction set\n\n```scheme\n(define instruction-set\n  '(push        ;; push a value on stack\n    lookup      ;; look up a variable from env\n    add         ;; add top two on stack\n    mul         ;; multiply top two on stack\n    jump-if-false ;; conditional jump\n    ret))       ;; return\n\n(for-each (lambda (i) (display i) (newline)) instruction-set)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\npush\nlookup\nadd\nmul\njump-if-false\nret\n```\n\nSix instructions. A minimal ISA.\n\n## Compiling a number\n\n```scheme\n(define (compile-number n)\n  (list (list 'push n)))\n\n(display (compile-number 42)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n((push 42))\n```\n\n## Compiling addition\n\n```scheme\n(define (compile-add a b)\n  (append (compile-number a)\n           (compile-number b)\n           (list (list 'add))))\n\n(display (compile-add 3 5)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n((push 3) (push 5) (add))\n```\n\n## Compiling a variable reference\n\n```scheme\n(define (compile-var name)\n  (list (list 'lookup name)))\n\n(display (compile-var 'x)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n((lookup x))\n```\n\n## Compiling an if\n\n```scheme\n(define (compile-if test then else)\n  (append\n    (compile-form test)\n    (list (list 'jump-if-false 'then-label))\n    (compile-form then)\n    (list (list 'jump 'end-label))\n    (list (list 'label 'then-label))\n    (compile-form else)\n    (list (list 'label 'end-label))))\n\n(define (compile-form form)\n  (cond\n    ((number? form) (compile-number form))\n    ((symbol? form) (compile-var form))\n    (else '((unimplemented)))))\n\n(display (compile-if 'x 42 100)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n((lookup x) (jump-if-false then-label) (push 42) (jump end-label) (label then-label) (push 100) (label end-label))\n```\n\n## Book closing shape\n\n```scheme\n(define reference-vocabulary\n  '((conway              chapter-1)\n    (sorting-viz         chapter-2)\n    (tail-recursion      chapter-3)\n    (macros              chapter-4)\n    (sicp-flavor         chapter-5)\n    (metacircular        chapter-6)\n    (streams             chapter-7)\n    (continuations       chapter-8)\n    (environments        chapter-9)\n    (a-tiny-compiler     chapter-10)))\n\n(for-each (lambda (p) (display p) (newline)) reference-vocabulary)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(conway chapter-1)\n(sorting-viz chapter-2)\n(tail-recursion chapter-3)\n(macros chapter-4)\n(sicp-flavor chapter-5)\n(metacircular chapter-6)\n(streams chapter-7)\n(continuations chapter-8)\n(environments chapter-9)\n(a-tiny-compiler chapter-10)\n```\n\nTen chapters. One arc: from Conway to a working compiler.\n\n## What you know now\n\n- A compiler produces instructions for a simpler machine.\n- Six instructions can cover a lot.\n- Compilation walks the form recursively, emitting instructions per case.\n- The compiled form runs faster than the interpreted form.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\n```scheme\n(display '(compiler-is-interpreter-that-produces-code-not-values)) (newline)\n```\n\nYou've walked the Book of Reference.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-6]] — metacircular.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-8]] — continuations.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-9]] — environments.\n")
